{{Infobox book | name = Blue Latitudes/Boldly Going Where Captain Cook Has Gone Before | title_orig = | translator = | image = Blue Latitudes.jpg | caption = | author = [[Tony Horwitz]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = English | series = | subject = [[James Cook]] | genre = [[Travel literature|Travel]] and [[History]] | publisher = [[Henry Holt and Company]] | pub_date = 2002 | english_pub_date = | media_type = [[Hardcover]], [[Paperback]], [[Audiobook]], [[E-Book]] | pages = 480 | isbn = 978-0-312-42260-8 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Blue Latitudes: Boldly Going Where Captain Cook Has Gone Before''''' (United States), or '''''Into the Blue: Boldly Going Where Captain Cook Has Gone Before''''' (Australia), is a [[Travel literature|travel book]] by [[Tony Horwitz]], published in 2002.
In it, the [[Pulitzer Prize]]–winning journalist travels to various parts of the world, following in the footsteps of explorer [[James Cook]]. The book compares the current conditions of the places Cook visited to what Cook documented at the time, and describes the different legacies Cook has left behind.<ref name=Harris>{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Robert R|title=Cook's Tour|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/22/books/cook-s-tour.html|accessdate=20 September 2014|agency=The New York Times|date=September 22, 2002}}</ref>
Horowitz begins with his experience as a volunteer deckhand on the [[HM Bark Endeavour Replica|replica of HM Bark ''Endeavour'']]. Some of the places Horowitz visits in his travels include Australia, the small island nation of [[Niue]], the [[Society Islands]], [[Tonga]], New Zealand, the birthplace and home of Cook in [[North Yorkshire]] England, [[Alaska]], and [[Hawaii]].
