===Dependent territories and states with limited recognition===
The following jurisdictions also rest inside the EBA borders, but cannot join the ITU or EBU due their dependent status or limited recognition:
;Dependent territories
*{{flag|Akrotiri and Dhekelia}}, [[British Overseas Territories|overseas territory]] of the [[United Kingdom]].
*{{flag|Faroe Islands}}, constituent country of [[Denmark]].
*{{flag|Gibraltar}}, [[British Overseas Territories|overseas territory]] of the United Kingdom.
*{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Bailiwick of Guernsey|Guernsey]], [[Crown dependency]] of the United Kingdom.
*{{flag|Isle of Man}}, Crown dependency of the United Kingdom.
*{{flag|Jersey}}, Crown dependency of the United Kingdom.
;States with limited recognition
*{{flag|Abkhazia}}, claimed as an [[Administrative divisions of Georgia (country)|autonomous republic]] of [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].
*{{flag|Artsakh}}, claimed as [[Administrative divisions of Azerbaijan|part]] of [[Azerbaijan]].
*{{flag|Kosovo}}, claimed as an [[Autonomous Province of Kosovo and Metohija|autonomous province]] of [[Serbia]].
*{{flag|Northern Cyprus}}, claimed as [[Districts of Cyprus|part]] of [[Cyprus]].
*{{flag|Palestine}}, [[Palestinian territories|disputed]] by [[Israel]].
*{{flag|South Ossetia}}, claimed as [[Administrative divisions of Georgia (country)|part]] of Georgia.
*{{flag|Transnistria}}, claimed as a [[Administrative divisions of Moldova|territorial unit]] of [[Moldova]].
*{{flag|Kurdistan}} (including {{flag|Rojava}} in Syria) autonomous region of Iraq, disputed by Turkey, Syria, and Iran.

== Companies in the European Broadcasting Area ==
{{Cleanup rewrite|A lot of unneeded info in every section. The Germany section makes no mention of ARD or ZDF, the two 'main' broadcasters, yet has three regional broadcasters. Sweden includes the non-existent channels of 'SVT3' & 'SVT4'. The UK has listed 'Sianel 4 Cymru', 'UK STV', and 'United Kingdom Independent Broadcasting' separately, despite the first two along with ITV and Channel 4 making up 'UKIB'|section|date=April 2018}}
'''Overview'''

The members of the ''[[European Broadcasting Union]]'' are able to provide their audience with a variety of channels in different countries. Every country included in the European Broadcasting Area consists of different companies that spread the news to the public in a multitude of ways. Below are some countries and the companies that deliver information and entertainment to their viewers in the European Broadcasting Area.

'''Companies'''

'''Algeria'''

The companies in Algeria are Etablissement Public de Radiodiffusion Sonore, Etablissment Public de Télévision Algérienne, and Télédiffusion d’Algérie. The Etablissement Public de Radiodiffusion Sonore is the main radio company in Algeria. It consists of three different radio stations that transmit programs talking about regional, local, or international life related to Algerian nationalism. There are three different radio national channels because each one transmits programs in different languages. The first channel transmits information in Arabic while the second and third channel use the French language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radioalgerie.dz/news/fr/about|title=A propos de la Radio Algérienne {{!}} Radio Algérienne|website=www.radioalgerie.dz|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> The Etablissment Public de Télévision Algérienne is the main television company in Algeria. The company’s main motive is the same as Algeria’s radio company which is to educate and entertain their audience with programs about regional, local, and international life along with current events from around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.entv.dz/tvfr/dossiers/index.php?id=4&voir=314|title=.::ETABLISSENT PUBLIC DE TELEVISION ::.|last=alger-contact@entv.dz|first=All: ENTV [www.entv.dz]; e-mail:|website=www.entv.dz|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> The company transmits their channel to Europe, North Africa, and parts of the Middle East. The Télédiffusion d’Algérie is in charge of distributing radio and television channels and programs through technological advancements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tda.dz/fr/Radiodiffusion|title=TDA{{!}} Radiodiffusion|website=www.tda.dz|access-date=2016-10-21|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104014414/https://www.tda.dz/fr/Radiodiffusion|archivedate=2016-11-04|df=}}</ref>

'''Belgium'''

In Belgium, the companies are [[RTBF|Radio-Télévision Belge de la Communauté française]] and [[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie|Vlaamse Radio en Televisieomroep]]. Radio-Télévision Belge de la Communauté française (RTBF) is a public corporation that is focused on the needs of French speaking Belgian citizens and their aspiration is to educate and entertain their audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rtbf.be/entreprise/a-propos#notre-organisation|title=À Propos de la RTBF|website=RTBF Entreprises|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> Their ways of distributing information are four television channels, six radio stations, their webpage, and social networks. The Vlaamse Radio en Televisieomroep is a public service broadcasting company for Flemish people. Their focus is to provide information about the Flemish culture and identity in an open and diverse way.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vrt.be/wie-zijn-we|title=Wie zijn we {{!}} VRT|website=www.vrt.be|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> The company consists of a few radio stations and television news and sports programs.

'''Denmark'''

In Denmark, the companies are [[DR (broadcaster)|Danmarks Radio]] and [[TV 2 (Denmark)|TV 2 DANMARK]]. Danmarks Radio (DR) is the oldest Danish Broadcasting Corporation in Denmark with regard to electronic media business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dr.dk/om-dr/about-dr|title=About dr|website=DR|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> Danmarks Radio broadcasts information about news and entertainment through six television channels, nine radio channels, orchestras, and apps. TV 2 DANMARK is a government-owned company and is Denmark’s most watched channel with a number of sister channels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://omtv2.tv2.dk/fakta/tv-2-i-overskrifter/|title=TV 2 I OVERSKRIFTER|website=Om TV 2|language=da-DK|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref>

'''Ireland'''

The companies in Ireland are [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann]] and [[TG4]]. Raidió Teilifís Éireann (RTÉ) is a public media organization in Ireland that grants their audience extensive multi-media services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/about/en/how-rte-is-run/2014/0310/601244-about-rte/|title=About RTÉ- Watch, Listen, Discover|last=|first=|date=|website=RTÉ About|publisher=RTÉ.ie|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> RTÉ distributes their programs over seven television channels, nine radio stations, and their website. TG4 is a television channel known for its use of the Irish language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tg4.ie/ga/corporate/background/|title=Buneolas {{!}} TG4|newspaper=TG4|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-16}}</ref> [[TV3_(Ireland)|TV3]] is an independent channel that is available on every television in Ireland with an average of 650,000 people tuning in to watch it a day.

'''France'''

Some of the companies in France are [[France Télévisions]], France Médias Monde, and [[Radio France]]. France Télévisions is a television company owned by the government. It became France Télévisions with the consolidation of the television channels France 2, France 3, France 4, France 5, and France Ô.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.onlinereporter.com/2011/09/13/french-public-broadcaster-goes-for-hbbtv/|title=French Public Broadcaster Goes for HbbTV|date=2011-09-13|website=The Online Reporter|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> France Médias Monde controls France 24, RFI, and Monte Carlo Doualiya.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.francemediasmonde.com/page/presentation-mission.html|title=France Médias Monde|website=www.francemediasmonde.com|access-date=2016-10-21|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160421123705/http://www.francemediasmonde.com/page/presentation-mission.html|archivedate=2016-04-21|df=}}</ref> The company is an international broadcasting service that transmits from the South of France to different parts of the world. France 24 is the international news channel, RFI is the international radio station, and Monte Carol Doualiya is an Arab-speaking radio station. Radio France is a national broadcasting company made up of seven other channels and forty-four local stations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiofrance.fr/l-entreprise/reperes|title=Repères - Radio France|website=www.radiofrance.fr|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>

'''Germany'''

Some of the companies in Germany are [[Deutsche Welle]], [[Deutschlandradio|Deutschland Radio]], [[Rundfunk Berlin-Brandenburg|Rundfunk Berlin- Brandenburg]], Saarländischer Rundfunk, and [[Südwestrundfunk]]. Deutsche Welle (DW) is Germany’s international broadcasting service. DW is made up of six channels that transmit in 30 different languages internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/about-dw/profile/s-30688|title=Profile {{!}} DW.COM|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Deutschland Radio is the German radio that consists of three programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deutschlandradio.de/geschichte.2091.de.html|title=Geschichte|website=Deutschlandradio|language=de-DE|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> The German radio is a sign of nationalism because Germany did not have radio like other countries. The three programs are Germany Spark, Germany Kultur, and DRadio Knowledge. Germany Spark focuses on broadcasting information and is based in Cologne. Germany Kultur focuses on culture in the nation. Dradio Knowledge is an entertainment program that broadcasts pop culture news and music. Rundfunk Berlin- Brandenburg (RBB) is a merger of Sander Freies Berlin (SFB) company and the East German Rundfunk Brandenburg (ORB).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rbb-online.de/unternehmen/der_rbb/geschichte/Geschichte_des_rbb.html|title=Geschichte des rbb|website=www.rbb-online.de|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>  RBB consists of broadcasting information through television and radio channels. Saarländischer Rundfunk (SR) is a radio and television company in Germany. SR consists of four radio stations and three television programs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sr.de/sr/home/der_sr/index.html|title=Der SR|last=Rundfunk|first=Saarländischer|date=2016-10-21|newspaper=SR.de|language=de-DE|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Südwestrundfunk (SWR) is a public media company with many radio and television programs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.swr.de/unternehmen/organisation/das-ist-der-swr/-/id=7687068/did=12277828/nid=7687068/v9ukzm/index.html|title=Das ist der SWR {{!}} Organisation {{!}} Unternehmen|newspaper=swr.online|language=de-DE|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> The SWR programs consist of SWR1, SWR 2, SWR 3, SWR 4, SWRinfo, DASDING, and SWR Classic.

'''Netherlands'''

In the Netherlands, some companies are KRO-NCRV, NTR, [[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting]], [[Nederlandse Publieke Omroep (organization)|Nerderlandse Publieke Omroep]], and Omroep MAX. KRO-NCRV is a collaboration broadcaster made up of the association of KRO and the NCRV association.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kro-ncrv.nl/370-33391-over-de-kro-ncrv|title=Over de KRO-NCRV|newspaper=KRO-NCRV|access-date=2016-10-21|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020234854/http://www.kro-ncrv.nl/370-33391-over-de-kro-ncrv|archivedate=2016-10-20|df=}}</ref> The company provides their audience with information about their society, their culture, and social needs. NTR an independent public service broadcaster that provides their viewers with unique programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ntr.nl/site/tekst/over-ntr/8#content|title=Over NTR|last=NTR|first=Omroep|website=NTR|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Nederlandse Omroep Stichting (NOS) is a television company that transmits national Dutch news and international news.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://over.nos.nl/onze-programmas|title=Over de NOS - Onze programma's|website=over.nos.nl|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> NOS provides the Dutch viewers with information about news, sports, and events with a number of television programs. Nerderlandse Publieke Omroep (NPO) is a public service broadcaster for any who wants to watch or listen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://over.npo.nl/|title=Over NPO - NPO|website=over.npo.nl|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> NPO broadcasts through television and radio programs and social media. Omroep MAX is a public broadcasting service specially designed with programs for people of 50 years of age and older.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omroepmax.nl/over-max/over-omroep-max/omroep-max/|title=Omroep MAX|website=Omroep MAX|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>

'''Sweden'''

In Sweden, the companies are Sveriges Radio Ab, Sverieges Television Sb, Swedish Educational Broadcasting Company. Sveriges Radio Ab (SR) is an independent radio company for the Swedish population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=3113&artikel=1971435|title=Uppdrag - Företagsfakta - Om Sveriges Radio|last=Radio|first=Sveriges|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> The company consists of 13 radio stations that broadcasts different information. Radio station P1 is for qualified news, P2 is for classical, jazz, and folk music, P3 is for mostly for the young adults with a variety of programs, P4 is for national and international news and pop music, etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=3113&artikel=1971544|title=Kanaler och frekvenser - Företagsfakta - Om Sveriges Radio|last=Radio|first=Sveriges|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Sverieges Television Ab (SVT) is Sweden’s public service television company. SVT consists of four channels which are SVT1, SVT2, SVT3, SVT4.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.svt.se/aboutsvt/the-swedish-public-service-broadcaster|title=SVT - the Swedish public service broadcaster {{!}} SVT.se|last=Sweden|first=Sveriges Television AB, Stockholm,|website=www.svt.se|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Swedish Educational Broadcasting Company (UR) is in collaboration with SR and SVT and focuses on broadcasting educational programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ur.se/about-ur|title=About UR|website=Sveriges Utbildningsradio, UR|language=sv-SE|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>

'''United Kingdom'''

The United Kingdom’s companies are [[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]], Sianel 4 Cymru, UK STV, and [[United Kingdom Independent Broadcasting]]. British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) is a public service broadcaster in the UK and the world through various television channels, radio stations, and online websites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/aboutthebbc/insidethebbc/whoweare/ataglance|title=BBC - At A Glance - Inside the BBC|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Sianel 4 Cymru (S4C) is a public service broadcaster that transmits Welsh language programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.s4c.cymru/abouts4c/c_index.shtml|title=S4C Amdanom ni|website=www.s4c.cymru|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> Also, it is the only Welsh-speaking channel in the whole world. The channel broadcasts more than 155 hours of programming a week. UK STV is Scotland’s digital media company. STV broadcasts their programs on TV, on demand, and online.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stv.tv/info/about/|title=About STV|website=STV Information|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref> United Kingdom Independent Broadcasting (ITV) is a producer broadcaster with the availability of many different channels for their viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.itvplc.com/about/what-we-do|title=Who we are {{!}} itvplc|website=itvplc|access-date=2016-10-21}}</ref>

